            <p>S. MORAIS&#44;<lb/>
                546 NORTH FIFTH ST.&#44;<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Judge Myer S. Isaacs		N. Y..<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia&#44; October 10th 1888<lb/></p>
            <p>My Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Any day would suit me better than<lb/> Sunday&#44; but&#44; aside from that consideration&#44; I deem it advisable<lb/> not to let Mr Miller know that I brought about<lb/> the settlement of the open negotiation.  As I have<lb/> already mentioned&#44; <del>to you</del>&#44; Miller is doubtless aware of the<lb/> petition sent to the Baron&#44; of the expectations of<lb/> the colonists&#44; and I believe that&#44; <del>under</del> with the <del>impression</del> idea<lb/> that a large sum would be forthcoming&#44; he sold some<lb/> land&#44; on the very day I was at his place&#44; to men who<lb/> hoped to receive enough to pay up when would I hand<del>ed them</del> each<lb/> a check for two or three hundred Dollars.  Let<lb/> Miller remain under the impression that Mr Gold&#45;<lb/>man has procured the money.  There can be no &#91;&#63;&#93; in &#91;&#63;&#93; him.  Now&#44; regarding<lb/> the land&#44; I wish to say that others&#44; besides Miller&#44;<lb/> own a portion&#44; and the quantity and the indebted<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>&#45;ness ought to be ascertained&#44; in order to fully carry<lb/> out Mr Veneziani&#39;s <del>ideas and</del> instruction.  The<lb/> memorial which I endorsed was signed by sixty six<lb/> persons&#44; if I well remember.  Many of them may<lb/> not be entitled to a grant&#44; but there are many also<lb/> who in all likelihood deserve to be assisted.  Mr<lb/> Goldman who has taken an interest in the colony<lb/> heretofore&#44; must <del>know</del> understand all particulars&#44; but as I<lb/> act in the name of the philanthropic donor&#44; I find<lb/> it necessary to present things in the light<lb/> I view them.  I shall be glad to meet<lb/> you and Dr G.&#44; and if you let me know where<lb/> <del>I can meet find you</del> you will be can early on Sunday morning&#44; I will merely<lb/> be there&#44; G. W. to have a talk.  Let us act carefully&#44;<lb/> so that we may U do the colonists no injustice&#44; but still&#44;<lb/> carrying out the Baron&#39;s intentions&#44; <del>without</del> we do not en&#45;<lb/>courage<del>ing</del> dishonest speculators.<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours truly<lb/>
                S. Morais<lb/></p>
            </body>
